                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 164.—<name type="person" key="698">Private John Hutton</name>,
                                                <name type="organization" key="433">Co. D, 1st Vt.
                                                Cav.</name>, was admitted <date type="admit" when="1863-11-23">Nov. 23, 1863</date>, delirious.
                                        He rolled from side to side in bed and picked at the
                                        bedclothes; his tongue and skin were dry, his pulse small
                                        and his feet cold; involuntary stools were passed frequently. Stimulants were given and warmth and
                                        mustard applied to his feet and legs.  He died on <date type="death" when="1863-11-27">the 27th</date>.  <hi rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi> examination <date type="autopsy" when="1863-11-28">twelve
                                        hours after death</date>: Body not emaciated; both feet gangrenous.
                                        Heart and lungs healthy. Spleen enlarged and of a
                                        dark-purple color; kidneys healthy; mesenteric glands
                                        enlarged; Peyer's glands enlarged and ulcerated; solitary
                                        glands of large intestine ulcerated.—<hi rend="italic"><name type="person" key="210">Act.
                                                  Ass't Surg. W. H. Letterman</name>, <name type="hospital" key="162">Douglas Hospital</name>,
                                                Washington, D. C.</hi></p>                        
